A1-218.name: Old Amber
A1-218.rule: You may play any number of Item cards during your turn.

A1-283.name: Mew

attack.effect: Your opponent reveals their hand.

A1-283.text:
Because it can use all kinds of moves, many
scientists believe Mew to be the ancestor
of Pokémon.

A1-001.name: Bulbasaur
A1-001.text:
There is a plant seed on its back right from the
day this Pokémon is born. The seed slowly
grows larger.

A1-002.name: Ivysaur
A1-002.text:
When the bulb on its back grows large, it
appears to lose the ability to stand on its
hind legs.

A1-003.name: Venusaur

attack.effect: Heal 30 damage from this Pokémon.

A1-003.text:
Its plant blooms when it is absorbing solar
energy. It stays on the move to seek sunlight.

A1-004.name: Venusaur ex

attack.effect: Heal 30 damage from this Pokémon.

A1-004.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-008.name: Weedle
A1-008.text:
Often found in forests and grasslands.
It has a sharp, toxic barb of around two inches
on top of its head.

A1-009.name: Kakuna
A1-009.text:
Almost incapable of moving, this Pokémon can only
harden its shell to protect itself when it is
in danger.

A1-010.name: Beedrill
A1-010.text:
It has three poisonous stingers on its forelegs and
its tail. They are used to jab its enemy repeatedly.

A1-016.name: Venonat
A1-016.text:
Poison oozes from all over its body. It catches
small bug Pokémon at night that are attracted
by light.

A1-017.name: Venomoth

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1-017.text:
The wings are covered with dustlike scales. Every
time it flaps its wings, it looses highly toxic dust.

A1-025.name: Scyther
A1-025.text:
It slashes through grass with its sharp
scythes, moving too fast for the human
eye to track.

A1-026.name: Pinsir

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 50 damage for each heads.

A1-026.text:
These Pokémon judge one another based on
pincers. Thicker, more impressive pincers make
for more popularity with the opposite gender.

A1-028.name: Whimsicott
A1-028.text:
It scatters cotton all over the place as a prank. If
it gets wet, it’ll become too heavy to move and
have no choice but to answer for its mischief.

A1-029.name: Petilil

attack.effect: Heal 10 damage from this Pokémon.

A1-029.text:
The leaves on its head grow right back even if
they fall out. These bitter leaves refresh those
who eat them.

A1-030.name: Lilligant

attack.effect: Take a {G} Energy from your Energy Zone and attach it to 1 of your Benched {G} Pokémon.

A1-030.text:
The fragrance of the garland on its head has
a relaxing effect, but taking care of it is very
difficult.

A1-042.name: Ponyta
A1-042.text:
It can’t run properly when it’s newly born.
As it races around with others of its kind,
its legs grow stronger.

A1-048.name: Heatmor
A1-048.text:
There’s a hole in its tail that allows it to draw in
the air it needs to keep its fire burning. If the
hole gets blocked, this Pokémon will fall ill.

A1-049.name: Salandit
A1-049.text:
It taunts its prey and lures them into narrow,
rocky areas where it then sprays them with toxic
gas to make them dizzy and take them down.

A1-050.name: Salazzle
A1-050.text:
Salazzle makes its opponents light-headed with
poisonous gas, then captivates them with alluring
movements to turn them into loyal servants.

A1-052.name: Centiskorch

attack.effect: Discard a {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-052.text:
When it heats up, its body temperature reaches
about 1,500 degrees Fahrenheit. It lashes its
body like a whip and launches itself at enemies.

A1-062.name: Tentacool
A1-062.text:
Tentacool is not a particularly strong swimmer.
It drifts across the surface of shallow seas as it
searches for prey.

A1-063.name: Tentacruel

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1-063.text:
When the red orbs on Tentacruel’s head glow
brightly, watch out. The Pokémon is about to
fire off a burst of ultrasonic waves.

A1-066.name: Shellder
A1-066.text:
It is encased in a shell that is harder than diamond.
Inside, however, it is surprisingly tender.

A1-067.name: Cloyster

ability.effect: This Pokémon takes −10 damage from attacks.

A1-067.text:
Cloyster that live in seas with harsh tidal currents
grow large, sharp spikes on their shells.

A1-068.name: Krabby
A1-068.text:
It can be found near the sea. The large pincers
grow back if they are torn out of their sockets.

A1-069.name: Kingler

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. If both of them are heads, this attack does 80 more damage.

A1-069.text:
Its large and hard pincer has 10,000-horsepower
strength. However, being so big, it is unwieldy
to move.

A1-080.name: Vaporeon

attack.effect: Heal 30 damage from this Pokémon.

A1-080.text:
It lives close to water. Its long tail is ridged with
a fin, which is often mistaken for a mermaid’s.

A1-083.name: Articuno

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

A1-083.text:
It’s said that this Pokémon’s beautiful blue wings
are made of ice. Articuno flies over snowy
mountains, its long tail fluttering along behind it.

A1-084.name: Articuno ex

attack.effect: This attack also does 10 damage to each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1-084.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-091.name: Bruxish

attack.effect: If your opponent's Active Pokémon has damage on it, this attack does 60 more damage.

A1-091.text:
It grinds its teeth with great force to stimulate
its brain. It fires the psychic energy created by
this process from the protuberance on its head.

A1-107.name: Tynamo
A1-107.text:
While one alone doesn’t have much power,
a chain of many Tynamo can be as powerful
as lightning.

A1-108.name: Eelektrik
A1-108.text:
They coil around foes and shock them with
electricity-generating organs that seem simply
to be circular patterns.

A1-109.name: Eelektross

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

A1-109.text:
They crawl out of the ocean using their arms.
They will attack prey on shore and immediately
drag it into the ocean.

A1-110.name: Helioptile
A1-110.text:
When spread, the frills on its head act like solar
panels, generating the power behind this
Pokémon’s electric moves.

A1-111.name: Heliolisk

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 40 more damage.

A1-111.text:
One Heliolisk basking in the sun with its frill
outspread is all it would take to produce enough
electricity to power a city.

A1-112.name: Pincurchin

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

A1-112.text:
This Pokémon generates electricity when it
digests food. It uses its five hard teeth to scrape
seaweed off surfaces and eat it.

A1-119.name: Slowbro
A1-119.text:
When a Slowpoke went hunting in the sea, its tail
was bitten by a Shellder. That made it evolve
into Slowbro.

A1-120.name: Gastly
A1-120.text:
It wraps its opponent in its gas-like body,
slowly weakening its prey by poisoning it
through the skin.

A1-121.name: Haunter
A1-121.text:
It likes to lurk in the dark and tap shoulders
with a gaseous hand. Its touch causes endless
shuddering.

A1-122.name: Gengar

attack.effect: Your opponent can't use any Supporter cards from their hand during their next turn.

A1-122.text:
To steal the life of its target, it slips into
the prey’s shadow and silently waits for
an opportunity.

A1-123.name: Gengar ex

ability.effect: As long as this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, your opponent can’t use any Supporter cards from their hand.

A1-123.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-126.name: Mr. Mime

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes -20 damage from attacks.

A1-126.text:
The broadness of its hands may be no
coincidence—many scientists believe its palms
became enlarged specifically for pantomiming.

A1-127.name: Jynx

attack.effect: This attack does 20 more damage for each Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-127.text:
Its strange cries sound like human language.
There are some musicians who compose songs
for Jynx to sing.

A1-128.name: Mewtwo

attack.effect: Discard 2 {P} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-128.text:
It was created by a scientist after years of horrific
gene-splicing and DNA-engineering experiments.

A1-129.name: Mewtwo ex

attack.effect: Discard 2 {P} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-129.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-130.name: Ralts
A1-130.text:
The horns on its head provide a strong power
that enables it to sense people’s emotions.

A1-131.name: Kirlia
A1-131.text:
It has a psychic power that enables it to distort
the space around it and see into the future.

A1-132.name: Gardevoir

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may take a Energy from your Energy Zone and attach it to the Pokémon in the Active Spot.

A1-132.text:
To protect its Trainer, it will expend all its psychic
power to create a small black hole.

A1-138.name: Sandslash
A1-138.text:
The drier the area Sandslash lives in, the harder
and smoother the Pokémon’s spikes will feel
when touched.

A1-151.name: Cubone

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, attacks used by the Defending Pokémon do -20 damage.

A1-151.text:
When the memory of its departed mother brings
it to tears, its cries echo mournfully within the
skull it wears on its head.

A1-152.name: Marowak
A1-152.text:
This Pokémon overcame its sorrow to evolve a
sturdy new body. Marowak faces its opponents
bravely, using a bone as a weapon.

A1-153.name: Marowak ex

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 80 damage for each heads.

A1-153.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-154.name: Hitmonlee

attack.effect: This attack does 30 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1-154.text:
This amazing Pokémon has an awesome sense of
balance. It can kick in succession from any position.

A1-156.name: Rhyhorn
A1-156.text:
Strong, but not too bright, this Pokémon can
shatter even a skyscraper with its charging tackles.

A1-157.name: Rhydon
A1-157.text:
It begins walking on its hind legs after evolution.
It can punch holes through boulders with its horn.

A1-162.name: Clobbopus
A1-162.text:
It’s very curious, but its means of investigating
things is to try to punch them with its tentacles.
The search for food is what brings it onto land.

A1-163.name: Grapploct

attack.effect: Switch out your opponent's Active Pokémon to the Bench. (Your opponent chooses the new Active Pokémon.)

A1-163.text:
A body made up of nothing but muscle makes
the grappling moves this Pokémon performs with
its tentacles tremendously powerful.

A1-172.name: Zubat
A1-172.text:
It emits ultrasonic waves from its mouth to check
its surroundings. Even in tight caves, Zubat flies
around with skill.

A1-173.name: Golbat
A1-173.text:
It loves to drink other creatures’ blood. It’s said
that if it finds others of its kind going hungry,
it sometimes shares the blood it’s gathered.

A1-174.name: Grimer

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1-174.text:
Born from sludge, these Pokémon now gather
in polluted places and increase the bacteria in
their bodies.

A1-175.name: Muk

attack.effect: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is Poisoned, this attack does 50 more damage.

A1-175.text:
It’s thickly covered with a filthy, vile
sludge. It is so toxic, even its footprints
contain poison.

A1-176.name: Koffing
A1-176.text:
Its body is full of poisonous gas. It floats into
garbage dumps, seeking out the fumes of raw,
rotting trash.

A1-177.name: Weezing

ability.effect: Once during your turn, if this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, you may make your opponent’s Active Pokémon Poisoned.

A1-177.text:
If one of the twin Koffing inflates, the other one
deflates. It constantly mixes its poisonous gases.

A1-183.name: Dratini
A1-183.text:
It sheds many layers of skin as it grows larger.
During this process, it is protected by a rapid
waterfall.

A1-184.name: Dragonair
A1-184.text:
They say that if it emits an aura from its whole
body, the weather will begin to change instantly.

A1-185.name: Dragonite

attack.effect: 1 of your opponent's Pokémon is chosen at random 4 times. For each time a Pokémon was chosen, do 50 damage to it.

A1-185.text:
It is said that somewhere in the ocean lies an
island where these gather. Only they live there.

A1-186.name: Pidgey
A1-186.text:
A common sight in forests and woods. It flaps
its wings at ground level to kick up blinding sand.

A1-187.name: Pidgeotto
A1-187.text:
The claws on its feet are well developed.
It can carry prey such as an Exeggcute
to its nest over 60 miles away.

A1-188.name: Pidgeot

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may switch out your opponent’s Active Pokémon to the Bench. (Your opponent chooses the new Active Pokémon.)

A1-188.text:
When hunting, it skims the surface of water
at high speed to pick off unwary prey such
as Magikarp.

A1-189.name: Rattata
A1-189.text:
Its incisors grow continuously throughout its life.
If its incisors get too long, this Pokémon
becomes unable to eat, and it starves to death.

A1-201.name: Lickitung

attack.effect: Flip a coin until you get tails. This attack does 60 damage for each heads.

A1-201.text:
If this Pokémon’s sticky saliva gets on you and
you don’t clean it off, an intense itch will set in.
The itch won’t go away, either.

A1-205.name: Ditto

attack.effect: Choose 1 of your opponent's Pokémon's attacks and use it as this attack. If this Pokémon doesn't have the necessary Energy to use that attack, this attack does nothing.

A1-205.text:
Its transformation ability is perfect. However,
if made to laugh, it can’t maintain its disguise.

A1-207.name: Eevee
A1-207.text:
Its ability to evolve into many forms allows it to
adapt smoothly and perfectly to any environment.

A1-209.name: Porygon

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may look at the top card of your deck.

A1-209.text:
State-of-the-art technology was used to create
Porygon. It was the first artificial Pokémon to be
created via computer programming.

A1-210.name: Aerodactyl

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent shuffles their Active Pokémon back into their deck.

A1-210.text:
This is a ferocious Pokémon from ancient times.
Apparently even modern technology is incapable
of producing a perfectly restored specimen.

A1-212.name: Minccino
A1-212.text:
The way it brushes away grime with its tail
can be helpful when cleaning. But its focus on
spotlessness can make cleaning more of a hassle.

A1-213.name: Cinccino

attack.effect: This attack does 30 damage for each of your Benched Pokémon.

A1-213.text:
Its body secretes oil that this Pokémon spreads
over its nest as a coating to protect it from dust.
Cinccino won’t tolerate even a speck of the stuff.

A1-222.name: Koga
A1-222.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-223.name: Giovanni
A1-223.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-227.name: Bulbasaur
A1-227.text:
There is a plant seed on its back right from the
day this Pokémon is born. The seed slowly
grows larger.

A1-239.name: Cubone

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, attacks used by the Defending Pokémon do -20 damage.

A1-239.text:
When the memory of its departed mother brings
it to tears, its cries echo mournfully within the
skull it wears on its head.

A1-242.name: Golbat
A1-242.text:
It loves to drink other creatures’ blood. It’s said
that if it finds others of its kind going hungry,
it sometimes shares the blood it’s gathered.

A1-243.name: Weezing

ability.effect: Once during your turn, if this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, you may make your opponent’s Active Pokémon Poisoned.

A1-243.text:
If one of the twin Koffing inflates, the other one
deflates. It constantly mixes its poisonous gases.

A1-244.name: Dragonite

attack.effect: 1 of your opponent's Pokémon is chosen at random 4 times. For each time a Pokémon was chosen, do 50 damage to it.

A1-244.text:
It is said that somewhere in the ocean lies an
island where these gather. Only they live there.

A1-245.name: Pidgeot

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may switch out your opponent’s Active Pokémon to the Bench. (Your opponent chooses the new Active Pokémon.)

A1-245.text:
When hunting, it skims the surface of water
at high speed to pick off unwary prey such
as Magikarp.

A1-247.name: Ditto

attack.effect: Choose 1 of your opponent's Pokémon's attacks and use it as this attack. If this Pokémon doesn't have the necessary Energy to use that attack, this attack does nothing.

A1-247.text:
Its transformation ability is perfect. However,
if made to laugh, it can’t maintain its disguise.

A1-249.name: Porygon

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may look at the top card of your deck.

A1-249.text:
State-of-the-art technology was used to create
Porygon. It was the first artificial Pokémon to be
created via computer programming.

A1-251.name: Venusaur ex

attack.effect: Heal 30 damage from this Pokémon.

A1-251.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-258.name: Articuno ex

attack.effect: This attack also does 10 damage to each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1-258.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-261.name: Gengar ex

ability.effect: As long as this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, your opponent can’t use any Supporter cards from their hand.

A1-261.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-262.name: Mewtwo ex

attack.effect: Discard 2 {P} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-262.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-264.name: Marowak ex

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 80 damage for each heads.

A1-264.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-269.name: Koga
A1-269.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-270.name: Giovanni
A1-270.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-275.name: Articuno ex

attack.effect: This attack also does 10 damage to each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1-275.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-277.name: Gengar ex

ability.effect: As long as this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, your opponent can’t use any Supporter cards from their hand.

A1-277.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-282.name: Mewtwo ex

attack.effect: Discard 2 {P} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-282.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-284.name: Charizard ex

attack.effect: Discard 2 {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-284.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-285.name: Pikachu ex

attack.effect: This attack does 30 damage for each of your Benched {L} Pokémon.

A1-285.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-011.name: Oddish
A1-011.text:
If exposed to moonlight, it starts to move.
It roams far and wide at night to scatter its seeds.

A1-012.name: Gloom
A1-012.text:
Its pistils exude an incredibly foul odor.
The horrid stench can cause fainting at a distance
of 1.25 miles.

A1-013.name: Vileplume

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A1-013.text:
It has the world’s largest petals. With every step,
the petals shake out heavy clouds of toxic pollen.

A1-018.name: Bellsprout
A1-018.text:
Even though its body is extremely skinny, it is
blindingly fast when catching its prey.

A1-019.name: Weepinbell
A1-019.text:
The leafy parts act as cutters for slashing foes.
It spits a fluid that dissolves everything.

A1-020.name: Victreebel

ability.effect: If this Pokémon is in the Active Spot, once during your turn, you may switch in 1 of your opponent’s Benched Basic Pokémon to the Active Spot.

A1-020.text:
Said to live in huge colonies deep in jungles,
although no one has ever returned from there.

A1-021.name: Exeggcute
A1-021.text:
Though it may look like it’s just a bunch of eggs,
it’s a proper Pokémon. Exeggcute communicates
with others of its kind via telepathy, apparently.

A1-022.name: Exeggutor

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 30 more damage.

A1-022.text:
Each of Exeggutor’s three heads is thinking
different thoughts. The three don’t seem to be
very interested in one another.

A1-023.name: Exeggutor ex

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 40 more damage.

A1-023.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-024.name: Tangela

attack.effect: Heal 10 damage from this Pokémon.

A1-024.text:
Hidden beneath a tangle of vines that grows
nonstop even if the vines are torn off, this
Pokémon’s true appearance remains a mystery.

A1-031.name: Skiddo

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing.

A1-031.text:
Until recently, people living in the mountains
would ride on the backs of these Pokémon to
traverse the mountain paths.

A1-032.name: Gogoat
A1-032.text:
It can sense the feelings of others by touching
them with its horns. This species has assisted
people with their work since 5,000 years ago.

A1-033.name: Charmander

attack.effect: Discard a {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-033.text:
It has a preference for hot things. When it rains,
steam is said to spout from the tip of its tail.

A1-034.name: Charmeleon
A1-034.text:
It has a barbaric nature. In battle, it whips its
fiery tail around and slashes away with sharp claws.

A1-035.name: Charizard

attack.effect: Discard 2 {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-035.text:
It spits fire that is hot enough to melt boulders.
It may cause forest fires by blowing flames.

A1-036.name: Charizard ex

attack.effect: Discard 2 {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-036.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-037.name: Vulpix

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, the Defending Pokémon can't attack during your opponent's next turn.

A1-037.text:
While young, it has six gorgeous tails. When it
grows, several new tails are sprouted.

A1-038.name: Ninetales

attack.effect: Discard a {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-038.text:
It is said to live 1,000 years, and each of its tails
is loaded with supernatural powers.

A1-044.name: Magmar
A1-044.text:
Magmar dispatches its prey with fire. But it
regrets this habit once it realizes that it has
burned its intended prey to a charred crisp.

A1-045.name: Flareon

attack.effect: Discard 1 {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-045.text:
Inhaled air is carried to its flame sac, heated, and
exhaled as fire that reaches over 3,000 degrees
Fahrenheit.

A1-046.name: Moltres

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing.

A1-046.text:
It’s one of the legendary bird Pokémon. When
Moltres flaps its flaming wings, they glimmer with
a dazzling red glow.

A1-047.name: Moltres ex

attack.effect: Flip 3 coins. Take an amount of {R} Energy from your Energy Zone equal to the number of heads and attach it to your Benched {R} Pokémon in any way you like.

A1-047.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-051.name: Sizzlipede
A1-051.text:
It stores flammable gas in its body and uses it to
generate heat. The yellow sections on its belly
get particularly hot.

A1-058.name: Golduck
A1-058.text:
When it swims at full speed using its long,
webbed limbs, its forehead somehow begins
to glow.

A1-059.name: Poliwag
A1-059.text:
For Poliwag, swimming is easier than walking.
The swirl pattern on its belly is actually part of
the Pokémon’s innards showing through the skin.

A1-060.name: Poliwhirl
A1-060.text:
Staring at the swirl on its belly causes drowsiness.
This trait of Poliwhirl’s has been used in place of
lullabies to get children to go to sleep.

A1-061.name: Poliwrath

ability.effect: If this Pokémon is in the Active Spot and is damaged by an attack from your opponent’s Pokémon, do 20 damage to the Attacking Pokémon.

A1-061.text:
Its body is solid muscle. When swimming through
cold seas, Poliwrath uses its impressive arms to
smash through drift ice and plow forward.

A1-074.name: Staryu
A1-074.text:
If you visit a beach at the end of summer, you’ll
be able to see groups of Staryu lighting up in a
steady rhythm.

A1-075.name: Starmie
A1-075.text:
This Pokémon has an organ known as its core.
The organ glows in seven colors when Starmie is
unleashing its potent psychic powers.

A1-076.name: Starmie ex
A1-076.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-079.name: Lapras

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has at least 3 extra {W} Energy attached, this attack does 70 more damage.

A1-079.text:
A smart and kindhearted Pokémon,
it glides across the surface of the sea while
its beautiful song echoes around it.

A1-085.name: Ducklett
A1-085.text:
When attacked, it uses its feathers to splash water,
escaping under cover of the spray.

A1-086.name: Swanna
A1-086.text:
Despite their elegant appearance, they can flap
their wings strongly and fly for thousands of miles.

A1-087.name: Froakie
A1-087.text:
It secretes flexible bubbles from its chest and back.
The bubbles reduce the damage it would otherwise
take when attacked.

A1-088.name: Frogadier
A1-088.text:
It can throw bubble-covered pebbles with precise
control, hitting empty cans up to a hundred feet away.

A1-089.name: Greninja

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may do 20 damage to 1 of your opponent’s Pokémon.

A1-089.text:
It creates throwing stars out of compressed water.
When it spins them and throws them at high speed,
these stars can split metal in two.

A1-090.name: Pyukumuku
A1-090.text:
It lives in warm, shallow waters. If it encounters a
foe, it will spit out its internal organs as a means
to punch them.

A1-115.name: Abra

attack.effect: Switch this Pokémon with 1 of your Benched Pokémon.

A1-115.text:
This Pokémon uses its psychic powers while it
sleeps. The contents of Abra’s dreams affect the
powers that the Pokémon wields.

A1-116.name: Kadabra
A1-116.text:
Using its psychic power, Kadabra levitates as it
sleeps. It uses its springy tail as a pillow.

A1-117.name: Alakazam

attack.effect: This attack does 30 more damage for each Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-117.text:
It has an incredibly high level of intelligence.
Some say that Alakazam remembers everything
that ever happens to it, from birth till death.

A1-118.name: Slowpoke
A1-118.text:
It is incredibly slow and dopey. It takes five
seconds for it to feel pain when under attack.

A1-133.name: Woobat
A1-133.text:
While inside a cave, if you look up and see lots
of heart-shaped marks lining the walls, it’s
evidence that Woobat live there.

A1-134.name: Swoobat
A1-134.text:
Emitting powerful sound waves tires it out.
Afterward, it won’t be able to fly for a
little while.

A1-141.name: Mankey
A1-141.text:
It lives in groups in the treetops. If it loses sight of
its group, it becomes infuriated by its loneliness.

A1-142.name: Primeape

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has damage on it, this attack does 60 more damage.

A1-142.text:
It becomes wildly furious if it even senses
someone looking at it. It chases anyone
that meets its glare.

A1-143.name: Machop
A1-143.text:
Its whole body is composed of muscles.
Even though it’s the size of a human child, it can
hurl 100 grown-ups.

A1-144.name: Machoke
A1-144.text:
Its muscular body is so powerful, it must wear a
power-save belt to be able to regulate
its motions.

A1-145.name: Machamp
A1-145.text:
It quickly swings its four arms to rock its
opponents with ceaseless punches and chops
from all angles.

A1-146.name: Machamp ex
A1-146.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-155.name: Hitmonchan
A1-155.text:
Its punches slice the air. They are launched at
such high speed, even a slight graze could cause
a burn.

A1-158.name: Kabuto
A1-158.text:
This species is almost entirely extinct. Kabuto
molt every three days, making their shells harder
and harder.

A1-159.name: Kabutops

attack.effect: Heal from this Pokémon the same amount of damage you did to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-159.text:
Kabutops slices its prey apart and sucks out
the fluids. The discarded body parts become
food for other Pokémon.

A1-164.name: Ekans
A1-164.text:
By dislocating its jaw, it can swallow prey larger
than itself. After a meal, it curls up and rests.

A1-165.name: Arbok

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, the Defending Pokémon can't retreat.

A1-165.text:
The latest research has determined that there
are over 20 possible arrangements of the
patterns on its stomach.

A1-178.name: Mawile

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, discard a random Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-178.text:
It uses its docile-looking face to lull foes into
complacency, then bites with its huge,
relentless jaws.

A1-181.name: Meltan

attack.effect: Take 1 {M} Energy from your Energy Zone and attach it to this Pokémon.

A1-181.text:
It dissolves and eats metal. Circulating liquid
metal within its body is how it generates energy.

A1-182.name: Melmetal

ability.effect: This Pokémon takes −20 damage from attacks.

A1-182.text:
At the end of its life-span, Melmetal will rust and
fall apart. The small shards left behind will
eventually be reborn as Meltan.

A1-190.name: Raticate
A1-190.text:
People say that it fled from its enemies by
using its small webbed hind feet to swim
from island to island in Alola.

A1-191.name: Spearow
A1-191.text:
Its reckless nature leads it to stand up to
others—even large Pokémon—if it has to protect
its territory.

A1-192.name: Fearow

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, discard a random Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-192.text:
Carrying food through Fearow’s territory is
dangerous. It will snatch the food away from
you in a flash!

A1-196.name: Meowth

attack.effect: Draw 1 card.

A1-196.text:
All it does is sleep during the daytime. At night,
it patrols its territory with its eyes aglow.

A1-197.name: Persian

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, discard a random card from your opponent's hand.

A1-197.text:
Although its fur has many admirers, it is tough to
raise as a pet because of its fickle meanness.

A1-200.name: Dodrio
A1-200.text:
An enemy that takes its eyes off any of the
three heads—even for a second—will get
pecked severely.

A1-203.name: Kangaskhan

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 30 damage for each heads.

A1-203.text:
Although it’s carrying its baby in a pouch on
its belly, Kangaskhan is swift on its feet. It
intimidates its opponents with quick jabs.

A1-204.name: Tauros
A1-204.text:
When Tauros begins whipping itself with its tails,
it’s a warning that the Pokémon is about to
charge with astounding speed.

A1-206.name: Eevee
A1-206.text:
Its ability to evolve into many forms allows it to
adapt smoothly and perfectly to any environment.

A1-215.name: Dubwool
A1-215.text:
Weave a carpet from its springy wool, and you end
up with something closer to a trampoline. You’ll
start to bounce the moment you set foot on it.

A1-217.name: Dome Fossil
A1-217.rule: You may play any number of Item cards during your turn.

A1-219.name: Erika
A1-219.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-221.name: Blaine
A1-221.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-225.name: Sabrina
A1-225.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-228.name: Gloom
A1-228.text:
Its pistils exude an incredibly foul odor.
The horrid stench can cause fainting at a distance
of 1.25 miles.

A1-229.name: Pinsir

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 50 damage for each heads.

A1-229.text:
These Pokémon judge one another based on
pincers. Thicker, more impressive pincers make
for more popularity with the opposite gender.

A1-230.name: Charmander

attack.effect: Discard a {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-230.text:
It has a preference for hot things. When it rains,
steam is said to spout from the tip of its tail.

A1-231.name: Rapidash
A1-231.text:
This Pokémon can be seen galloping through
fields at speeds of up to 150 mph, its fiery mane
fluttering in the wind.

A1-234.name: Lapras

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has at least 3 extra {W} Energy attached, this attack does 70 more damage.

A1-234.text:
A smart and kindhearted Pokémon,
it glides across the surface of the sea while
its beautiful song echoes around it.

A1-236.name: Alakazam

attack.effect: This attack does 30 more damage for each Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-236.text:
It has an incredibly high level of intelligence.
Some say that Alakazam remembers everything
that ever happens to it, from birth till death.

A1-237.name: Slowpoke
A1-237.text:
It is incredibly slow and dopey. It takes five
seconds for it to feel pain when under attack.

A1-246.name: Meowth

attack.effect: Draw 1 card.

A1-246.text:
All it does is sleep during the daytime. At night,
it patrols its territory with its eyes aglow.

A1-257.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-278.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

attack.effect: Discard 2 {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-280.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-005.name: Caterpie

attack.effect: Put 1 random {G} Pokémon from your deck into your hand.

A1-005.text:
For protection, it releases a horrible stench from
the antenna on its head to drive away enemies.

A1-006.name: Metapod
A1-006.text:
It is waiting for the moment to evolve. At this
stage, it can only harden, so it remains
motionless to avoid attack.

A1-007.name: Butterfree

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may heal 20 damage from each of your Pokémon.

A1-007.text:
In battle, it flaps its wings at great speed to
release highly toxic dust into the air.

A1-014.name: Paras
A1-014.text:
The mushrooms, known as tochukaso, are
controlling the bug. Even if the bug bugs the
mushrooms, they tell it to bug off.

A1-015.name: Parasect
A1-015.text:
The bug is mostly dead, with the mushroom on
its back having become the main body. If the
mushroom comes off, the bug stops moving.

A1-027.name: Cottonee
A1-027.text:
It shoots cotton from its body to protect itself.
If it gets caught up in hurricane-strength winds,
it can get sent to the other side of the Earth.

A1-039.name: Growlithe
A1-039.text:
It has a brave and trustworthy nature. It fearlessly
stands up to bigger and stronger foes.

A1-040.name: Arcanine

attack.effect: This Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

A1-040.text:
An ancient picture scroll shows that people
were captivated by its movement as it ran
through prairies.

A1-041.name: Arcanine ex

attack.effect: This Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

A1-041.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-043.name: Rapidash
A1-043.text:
This Pokémon can be seen galloping through
fields at speeds of up to 150 mph, its fiery mane
fluttering in the wind.

A1-053.name: Squirtle
A1-053.text:
When it retracts its long neck into its shell, it
squirts out water with vigorous force.

A1-054.name: Wartortle
A1-054.text:
It is recognized as a symbol of longevity. If its
shell has algae on it, that Wartortle is very old.

A1-055.name: Blastoise

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has at least 2 extra {W} Energy attached, this attack does 60 more damage.

A1-055.text:
It crushes its foe under its heavy body to cause
fainting. In a pinch, it will withdraw inside its shell.

A1-056.name: Blastoise ex

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has at least 2 extra {W} Energy attached, this attack does 60 more damage.

A1-056.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-057.name: Psyduck

attack.effect: Your opponent can't use any Supporter cards from their hand during their next turn.

A1-057.text:
It is constantly wracked by a headache. When the
headache turns intense, it begins using mysterious
powers.

A1-064.name: Seel
A1-064.text:
Thanks to its thick fat, cold seas don’t bother it
at all, but it gets tired pretty easily in
warm waters.

A1-065.name: Dewgong
A1-065.text:
It sunbathes on the beach after meals. The rise
in its body temperature helps its digestion.

A1-070.name: Horsea
A1-070.text:
Horsea makes its home in oceans with gentle
currents. If this Pokémon is under attack, it spits
out pitch-black ink and escapes.

A1-071.name: Seadra

attack.effect: This attack does 50 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon.

A1-071.text:
It’s the males that raise the offspring. While
Seadra are raising young, the spines on their
backs secrete thicker and stronger poison.

A1-072.name: Goldeen
A1-072.text:
Its dorsal, pectoral, and tail fins wave elegantly
in water. That is why it is known as the Water Dancer.

A1-073.name: Seaking

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing.

A1-073.text:
In autumn, its body becomes more fatty in
preparing to propose to a mate. It takes on
beautiful colors.

A1-077.name: Magikarp
A1-077.text:
An underpowered, pathetic Pokémon. It may
jump high on rare occasions but never more
than seven feet.

A1-078.name: Gyarados

attack.effect: Discard a random Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-078.text:
Once it appears, it goes on a rampage.
It remains enraged until it demolishes
everything around it.

A1-081.name: Omanyte
A1-081.text:
Because some Omanyte manage to escape after
being restored or are released into the wild by
people, this species is becoming a problem.

A1-082.name: Omastar

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, the Defending Pokémon can't attack.

A1-082.text:
Weighed down by a large and heavy shell,
Omastar couldn’t move very fast. Some say it
went extinct because it was unable to catch food.

A1-092.name: Snom
A1-092.text:
It eats snow that has accumulated on the ground.
It prefers soft, freshly fallen snow, so it will eat its
way up a mountain, aiming for the peak.

A1-093.name: Frosmoth

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A1-093.text:
Frosmoth senses air currents with its antennae.
It sends its scales drifting on frigid air, making
them fall like snow.

A1-094.name: Pikachu
A1-094.text:
When it is angered, it immediately discharges the
energy stored in the pouches in its cheeks.

A1-095.name: Raichu

attack.effect: Discard all Energy from this Pokémon.

A1-095.text:
Its tail discharges electricity into the ground,
protecting it from getting shocked.

A1-096.name: Pikachu ex

attack.effect: This attack does 30 damage for each of your Benched {L} Pokémon.

A1-096.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-097.name: Magnemite
A1-097.text:
The electromagnetic waves emitted by the units
at the sides of its head expel antigravity, which
allows it to float.

A1-098.name: Magneton

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may take a Energy from your Energy Zone and attach it to this Pokémon.

A1-098.text:
Three Magnemite are linked by a strong magnetic
force. Earaches will occur if you get too close.

A1-099.name: Voltorb
A1-099.text:
It rolls to move. If the ground is uneven, a sudden
jolt from hitting a bump can cause it to explode.

A1-100.name: Electrode
A1-100.text:
The more energy it charges up, the faster
it gets. But this also makes it more likely
to explode.

A1-101.name: Electabuzz

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 40 more damage. If tails, this Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

A1-101.text:
Many power plants keep Ground-type Pokémon
around as a defense against Electabuzz that
come seeking electricity.

A1-102.name: Jolteon

attack.effect: Flip 4 coins. This attack does 40 damage for each heads.

A1-102.text:
It concentrates the weak electric charges emitted
by its cells and launches wicked lightning bolts.

A1-103.name: Zapdos

attack.effect: This attack also does 30 damage to 1 of your Benched Pokémon.

A1-103.text:
This Pokémon has complete control over
electricity. There are tales of Zapdos nesting in
the dark depths of pitch-black thunderclouds.

A1-104.name: Zapdos ex

attack.effect: Flip 4 coins. This attack does 50 damage for each heads.

A1-104.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-105.name: Blitzle
A1-105.text:
When thunderclouds cover the sky, it will appear.
It can catch lightning with its mane and store
the electricity.

A1-106.name: Zebstrika

attack.effect: This attack does 30 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon.

A1-106.text:
When this ill-tempered Pokémon runs wild, it
shoots lightning from its mane in all directions.

A1-113.name: Clefairy
A1-113.text:
It is said that happiness will come to those who
see a gathering of Clefairy dancing under a
full moon.

A1-114.name: Clefable
A1-114.text:
A timid fairy Pokémon that is rarely seen, it will
run and hide the moment it senses people.

A1-124.name: Drowzee
A1-124.text:
It remembers every dream it eats. It rarely eats
the dreams of adults because children’s are much
tastier.

A1-125.name: Hypno

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may flip a coin. If heads, your opponent’s Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A1-125.text:
When it locks eyes with an enemy, it will use
a mix of psi moves, such as Hypnosis and
Confusion.

A1-135.name: Golett
A1-135.text:
They were sculpted from clay in ancient times.
No one knows why, but some of them are driven
to continually line up boulders.

A1-136.name: Golurk

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 100 damage for each heads.

A1-136.text:
Artillery platforms built into the walls of ancient
castles served as perches from which Golurk
could fire energy beams.

A1-137.name: Sandshrew
A1-137.text:
It loves to bathe in the grit of dry, sandy areas.
By sand bathing, the Pokémon rids itself of dirt
and moisture clinging to its body.

A1-139.name: Diglett
A1-139.text:
It lives about one yard underground, where it
feeds on plant roots. It sometimes appears
aboveground.

A1-140.name: Dugtrio

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from—and effects of—attacks done to this Pokémon.

A1-140.text:
Its three heads bob separately up and down to
loosen the soil nearby, making it easier for it
to burrow.

A1-147.name: Geodude
A1-147.text:
Geodude that have lived a long life have had all
their edges smoothed out until they’re totally
round. They also have a calm, quiet disposition.

A1-148.name: Graveler
A1-148.text:
It climbs up cliffs as it heads toward the peak
of a mountain. As soon as it reaches the summit,
it rolls back down the way it came.

A1-149.name: Golem

attack.effect: This Pokémon also does 50 damage to itself.

A1-149.text:
When Golem grow old, they stop shedding their
shells. Those that have lived a long, long time
have shells green with moss.

A1-150.name: Onix
A1-150.text:
As it digs through the ground, it absorbs many
hard objects. This is what makes its body so solid.

A1-160.name: Mienfoo
A1-160.text:
In one minute, a well-trained Mienfoo can chop
with its arms more than 100 times.

A1-161.name: Mienshao
A1-161.text:
When Mienshao comes across a truly challenging
opponent, it will lighten itself by biting off the
fur on its arms.

A1-166.name: Nidoran♀

attack.effect: Put 1 random Nidoran♂ from your deck onto your Bench.

A1-166.text:
Females are more sensitive to smells than males.
While foraging, they’ll use their whiskers to check
wind direction and stay downwind of predators.

A1-167.name: Nidorina
A1-167.text:
The horn on its head has atrophied. It’s thought
that this happens so Nidorina’s children won’t get
poked while their mother is feeding them.

A1-168.name: Nidoqueen

attack.effect: This attack does 50 more damage for each of your Benched Nidoking.

A1-168.text:
Nidoqueen is better at defense than offense.
With scales like armor, this Pokémon will shield
its children from any kind of attack.

A1-169.name: Nidoran♂
A1-169.text:
The horn on a male Nidoran’s forehead contains
a powerful poison. This is a very cautious
Pokémon, always straining its large ears.

A1-170.name: Nidorino
A1-170.text:
With a horn that’s harder than diamond, this
Pokémon goes around shattering boulders as it
searches for a moon stone.

A1-171.name: Nidoking

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1-171.text:
When it goes on a rampage, it’s impossible to
control. But in the presence of a Nidoqueen it’s
lived with for a long time, Nidoking calms down.

A1-179.name: Pawniard
A1-179.text:
Pawniard will fearlessly challenge even powerful
foes. In a pinch, it will cling to opponents and
pierce them with the blades all over its body.

A1-180.name: Bisharp
A1-180.text:
This Pokémon commands a group of several
Pawniard. Groups that are defeated in territorial
disputes are absorbed by the winning side.

A1-193.name: Jigglypuff
A1-193.text:
When its huge eyes waver, it sings a mysteriously
soothing melody that lulls its enemies to sleep.

A1-194.name: Wigglytuff
A1-194.text:
It has a very fine fur. Take care not to make it
angry, or it may inflate steadily and hit with a
body slam.

A1-195.name: Wigglytuff ex

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A1-195.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1-198.name: Farfetch’d
A1-198.text:
The stalk this Pokémon carries in its wings serves
as a sword to cut down opponents. In a dire
situation, the stalk can also serve as food.

A1-199.name: Doduo
A1-199.text:
A two-headed Pokémon that was discovered as a
sudden mutation. It runs at a pace of over 60 miles
per hour.

A1-202.name: Chansey
A1-202.text:
This kindly Pokémon lays highly nutritious eggs
and shares them with injured Pokémon or people.

A1-208.name: Eevee
A1-208.text:
Its ability to evolve into many forms allows it to
adapt smoothly and perfectly to any environment.

A1-211.name: Snorlax
A1-211.text:
It is not satisfied unless it eats over 880 pounds
of food every day. When it is done eating, it
goes promptly to sleep.

A1-214.name: Wooloo
A1-214.text:
Its curly fleece is such an effective cushion that
this Pokémon could fall off a cliff and stand right
back up at the bottom, unharmed.

A1-216.name: Helix Fossil
A1-216.rule: You may play any number of Item cards during your turn.

A1-220.name: Misty
A1-220.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-224.name: Brock
A1-224.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-226.name: Lt. Surge
A1-226.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A1-232.text:
When it retracts its long neck into its shell, it
squirts out water with vigorous force.

A1-233.name: Gyarados

attack.effect: Discard a random Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1-233.text:
Once it appears, it goes on a rampage.
It remains enraged until it demolishes
everything around it.

A1-235.name: Electrode
A1-235.text:
The more energy it charges up, the faster
it gets. But this also makes it more likely
to explode.

A1-238.name: Diglett
A1-238.text:
It lives about one yard underground, where it
feeds on plant roots. It sometimes appears
aboveground.

A1-240.name: Nidoqueen

A1-240.text:
Nidoqueen is better at defense than offense.
With scales like armor, this Pokémon will shield
its children from any kind of attack.

A1-241.name: Nidoking

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1-241.text:
When it goes on a rampage, it’s impossible to
control. But in the presence of a Nidoqueen it’s

A1-248.text:
Its ability to evolve into many forms allows it to
adapt smoothly and perfectly to any environment.

A1-250.name: Snorlax

It is not satisfied unless it eats over 880 pounds
of food every day. When it is done eating, it
goes promptly to sleep.

A1a-001.text:
Though it may look like it’s just a bunch of eggs,
it’s a proper Pokémon. Exeggcute communicates
with others of its kind via telepathy, apparently.

A1a-002.name: Exeggutor

attack.effect: This attack does 20 more damage for each Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1a-002.text:
Each of Exeggutor’s three heads is thinking
different thoughts. The three don’t seem to be
very interested in one another.

attack.effect: Flip a coin for each Energy attached to this Pokémon. This attack does 50 damage for each heads.

A1a-003.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1a-004.name: Snivy
A1a-004.text:
Being exposed to sunlight makes its movements
swifter. It uses vines more adeptly than its hands.

A1a-005.name: Servine
A1a-005.text:
It moves along the ground as if sliding. Its swift
movements befuddle its foes, and it then attacks
with a vine whip.

A1a-006.name: Serperior

ability.effect: Each Energy attached to your Pokémon provides 2 Energy. This effect doesn’t stack.

A1a-006.text:
It only gives its all against strong opponents who
are not fazed by the glare from Serperior’s
noble eyes.

A1a-007.name: Morelull
A1a-007.text:
Pokémon living in the forest eat the
delicious caps on Morelull’s head.
The caps regrow overnight.

A1a-008.name: Shiinotic

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A1a-008.text:
Its flickering spores lure in prey and put them to
sleep. Once this Pokémon has its prey snoozing,
it drains their vitality with its fingertips.

A1a-009.name: Dhelmise

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has at least 3 extra {G} Energy attached, this attack does 70 more damage.

A1a-009.text:
After a piece of seaweed merged with debris
from a sunken ship, it was reborn as this
ghost Pokémon.

A1a-010.name: Ponyta

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 30 more damage.

A1a-010.text:
It can’t run properly when it’s newly born.
As it races around with others of its kind,
its legs grow stronger.

A1a-011.name: Rapidash

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 60 more damage.

A1a-011.text:
This Pokémon can be seen galloping through
fields at speeds of up to 150 mph, its fiery mane
fluttering in the wind.

A1a-012.name: Magmar

attack.effect: Discard 2 {R} Energy from this Pokémon.

A1a-012.text:
Magmar dispatches its prey with fire. But it
regrets this habit once it realizes that it has
burned its intended prey to a charred crisp.

A1a-013.name: Larvesta
A1a-013.text:
This Pokémon was called the Larva That Stole
the Sun. The fire Larvesta spouts from its horns
can cut right through a sheet of iron.

A1a-014.name: Volcarona

attack.effect: Discard 2 {R} Energy from this Pokémon. This attack does 80 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon.

A1a-014.text:
Its burning body causes it to be unpopular in hot
parts of the world, but in cold ones, Volcarona is
revered as an embodiment of the sun.

A1a-015.name: Salandit

attack.effect: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is Poisoned, this attack does 40 more damage.

A1a-015.text:
It taunts its prey and lures them into narrow,
rocky areas where it then sprays them with toxic
gas to make them dizzy and take them down.

A1a-016.name: Salazzle

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1a-016.text:
Salazzle makes its opponents light-headed with
poisonous gas, then captivates them with alluring
movements to turn them into loyal servants.

A1a-017.name: Magikarp

attack.effect: Switch this Pokémon with 1 of your Benched Pokémon.

A1a-017.text:
An underpowered, pathetic Pokémon. It may
jump high on rare occasions but never more
than seven feet.

A1a-018.name: Gyarados ex

attack.effect: Discard a random Energy from among the Energy attached to all Pokémon (both yours and your opponent's).

A1a-018.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1a-019.name: Vaporeon

ability.effect: As often as you like during your turn, you may move a Energy from 1 of your Benched Pokémon to your Active Pokémon.

A1a-019.text:
It lives close to water. Its long tail is ridged with
a fin, which is often mistaken for a mermaid’s.

A1a-020.name: Finneon
A1a-020.text:
The line running down its side can store sunlight.
It shines vividly at night.

A1a-021.name: Lumineon

attack.effect: This attack does 50 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1a-021.text:
With its shining light, it lures its prey close.
However, the light also happens to attract
ferocious fish Pokémon—its natural predators.

A1a-022.name: Chewtle
A1a-022.text:
Its large front tooth is still growing in. When the
tooth itches, this Pokémon will bite another
Chewtle’s horn, and the two Pokémon will tussle.

A1a-023.name: Drednaw

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, discard a random Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A1a-023.text:
Its massive, jagged teeth can crush a
boulder in a single bite. This Pokémon
has an extremely vicious disposition.

A1a-024.name: Cramorant

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from—and effects of—attacks done to this Pokémon.

A1a-024.text:
It’s so strong that it can knock out some
opponents in a single hit, but it also may
forget what it’s battling midfight.

A1a-025.name: Pikachu

attack.effect: This attack does 10 damage for each of your Benched {L} Pokémon.

A1a-025.text:
When it is angered, it immediately discharges the
energy stored in the pouches in its cheeks.

A1a-026.name: Raichu

attack.effect: This attack also does 20 damage to each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1a-026.text:
Its tail discharges electricity into the ground,
protecting it from getting shocked.

A1a-027.name: Electabuzz

attack.effect: This attack does 40 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon.

A1a-027.text:
Many power plants keep Ground-type Pokémon
around as a defense against Electabuzz that
come seeking electricity.

A1a-028.name: Joltik
A1a-028.text:
Joltik can be found clinging to other Pokémon.
It’s soaking up static electricity because it can’t
produce a charge on its own.

A1a-029.name: Galvantula

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, the Defending Pokémon can't retreat.

A1a-029.text:
It launches electrified fur from its abdomen as its
means of attack. Opponents hit by the fur could
be in for three full days and nights of paralysis.

A1a-030.name: Dedenne

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Paralyzed.

A1a-030.text:
It’s small and its electricity-generating organ is
not fully developed, so it uses its tail to absorb
electricity from people’s homes and charge itself.

A1a-031.name: Mew

attack.effect: Your opponent reveals their hand.

A1a-031.text:
Because it can use all kinds of moves, many
scientists believe Mew to be the ancestor
of Pokémon.

A1a-032.name: Mew ex

attack.effect: Choose 1 of your opponent's Active Pokémon's attacks and use it as this attack.

A1a-032.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A1a-033.name: Sigilyph

attack.effect: Draw a card.

A1a-033.text:
Psychic power allows these Pokémon to fly. Some
say they were the guardians of an ancient city.
Others say they were the guardians’ emissaries.

A1a-034.name: Elgyem
A1a-034.text:
If this Pokémon stands near a TV, strange scenery
will appear on the screen. That scenery is said
to be from its home.

A1a-035.name: Beheeyem

attack.effect: This attack does 20 more damage for each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A1a-035.text:
Whenever a Beheeyem visits a farm,
a Dubwool mysteriously disappears.

A1a-036.name: Flabébé

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A1a-036.text:
This Pokémon can draw forth the power hidden
within blooming wild flowers. It is particularly
fond of red flowers.

A1a-037.name: Floette

attack.effect: Heal 10 damage from this Pokémon.

A1a-037.text:
This Pokémon draws forth what power is left in
withered flowers to make them healthy again.
It holds a red flower.

A1a-038.name: Florges

attack.effect: Heal 20 damage from each of your Pokémon.

A1a-038.text:
This Pokémon creates an impressive flower
garden in its territory. It draws forth the power
of the red flowers around its neck.

A1a-039.name: Swirlix
A1a-039.text:
It eats its own weight in sugar every day.
If it doesn’t get enough sugar, it becomes
incredibly grumpy.

A1a-040.name: Slurpuff
A1a-040.text:
By taking in a person’s scent, it can sniff out their
mental and physical condition. It’s hoped that
this skill will have many medical applications.

A1a-041.name: Mankey

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If tails, this attack does nothing.

A1a-041.text:
It lives in groups in the treetops. If it loses sight of
its group, it becomes infuriated by its loneliness.

A1a-042.name: Primeape
A1a-042.text:
It becomes wildly furious if it even senses
someone looking at it. It chases anyone
that meets its glare.

A1a-043.name: Geodude
A1a-043.text:
Geodude that have lived a long life have had all
their edges smoothed out until they’re totally
round. They also have a calm, quiet disposition.

A1a-044.name: Graveler
A1a-044.text:
It climbs up cliffs as it heads toward the peak
of a mountain. As soon as it reaches the summit,
it rolls back down the way it came.

A1a-045.name: Golem

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes −30 damage from attacks.

A1a-045.text:
When Golem grow old, they stop shedding their
shells. Those that have lived a long, long time
have shells green with moss.

A1a-047.text:
It slips into the shadows of others and mimics
their powers and movements. As it improves, it
becomes stronger than those it’s imitating.

A1a-048.name: Stonjourner
A1a-048.text:
The elemental composition of the rocks that
form its body were found to match the bedrock
of a land far away from this Pokémon’s habitat.

A1a-049.name: Koffing

attack.effect: Put 1 random Koffing from your deck onto your Bench.

A1a-049.text:
Its body is full of poisonous gas. It floats into
garbage dumps, seeking out the fumes of raw,
rotting trash.

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, if the Defending Pokémon tries to use an attack, your opponent flips a coin. If tails, that attack doesn't happen.

A1a-050.text:
If one of the twin Koffing inflates, the other one
deflates. It constantly mixes its poisonous gases.

A1a-051.name: Purrloin
A1a-051.text:
It steals things from people just to amuse itself
with their frustration. A rivalry exists between
this Pokémon and Nickit.

A1a-052.name: Liepard
A1a-052.text:
Don’t be fooled by its gorgeous fur and elegant
figure. This is a moody and vicious Pokémon.

A1a-053.name: Venipede
A1a-053.text:
Venipede and Sizzlipede are similar species,
but when the two meet, a huge fight ensues.

A1a-054.name: Whirlipede

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A1a-054.text:
This Pokémon spins itself rapidly and charges into
its opponents. Its top speed is just over 60 mph.

A1a-055.name: Scolipede

attack.effect: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is Poisoned, this attack does 50 more damage.

A1a-055.text:
Scolipede latches on to its prey with the claws on
its neck before slamming them into the ground
and jabbing them with its claws’ toxic spikes.

A1a-056.name: Druddigon

ability.effect: If this Pokémon is in the Active Spot and is damaged by an attack from your opponent’s Pokémon, do 20 damage to the Attacking Pokémon.

A1a-056.text:
Druddigon lives in caves, but it never skips
sunbathing—it won’t be able to move if its body
gets too cold.

A1a-057.name: Pidgey
A1a-057.text:
A common sight in forests and woods. It flaps
its wings at ground level to kick up blinding sand.

A1a-058.name: Pidgeotto
A1a-058.text:
The claws on its feet are well developed.
It can carry prey such as an Exeggcute
to its nest over 60 miles away.

charge with astounding speed.

A1a-061.text:
Its ability to evolve into many forms allows it to
adapt smoothly and perfectly to any environment.

A1a-062.name: Chatot

A1a-062.text:
It mimics the cries of other Pokémon to trick them
into thinking it’s one of them. This way they won’t
attack it.

A2-001.name: Oddish

attack.effect: Heal 10 damage from this Pokémon.

A2-001.text:
If exposed to moonlight, it starts to move.
It roams far and wide at night to scatter its seeds.

A2-002.name: Gloom
A2-002.text:
Its pistils exude an incredibly foul odor.
The horrid stench can cause fainting at a distance
of 1.25 miles.

A2-004.name: Tangela
A2-004.text:
Hidden beneath a tangle of vines that grows
nonstop even if the vines are torn off, this
Pokémon’s true appearance remains a mystery.

A2-005.name: Tangrowth

attack.effect: Heal 30 damage from this Pokémon.

A2-005.text:
Tangrowth has two arms that it can extend as it
pleases. Recent research has shown that these
arms are, in fact, bundles of vines.

A2-006.name: Yanma
A2-006.text:
Its eyes can see 360 degrees without moving its
head. It won’t miss prey—even those behind it.

A2-007.name: Yanmega ex

attack.effect: Discard a random Energy from this Pokémon.

A2-007.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A2-008.name: Roselia
A2-008.text:
Its flowers give off a relaxing fragrance.
The stronger its aroma, the healthier
the Roselia is.

A2-009.name: Roserade

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A2-009.text:
After captivating opponents with its sweet scent,
it lashes them with its thorny whips.

A2-015.name: Burmy
A2-015.text:
To shelter itself from cold, wintry winds, it covers
itself with a cloak made of twigs and leaves.

A2-017.name: Combee

attack.effect: Put 1 random Basic Pokémon from your deck onto your Bench.

A2-017.text:
At night, Combee sleep in a group of about a
hundred, packed closely together in a lump.

A2-018.name: Vespiquen
A2-018.text:
It houses its colony in cells in its body and
releases various pheromones to make those
grubs do its bidding.

A2-020.name: Leafeon

attack.effect: During your next turn, this Pokémon can't attack.

A2-020.text:
When you see Leafeon asleep in a patch of
sunshine, you’ll know it is using photosynthesis
to produce clean air.

A2-021.name: Mow Rotom

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, discard a random Energy from your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A2-021.text:
The lawn mower is one of the household
appliances that led to the development of
the Rotom Dex.

A2-022.name: Shaymin

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may heal 10 damage from each of your Pokémon.

A2-022.text:
It can dissolve toxins in the air to instantly
transform ruined land into a lush field of flowers.

A2-025.name: Slugma
A2-025.text:
A common sight in volcanic areas, it slowly slithers
around in a constant search for warm places.

A2-030.name: Heat Rotom

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 30 more damage.

A2-030.text:
If the convection microwave oven is not working
properly, then the Rotom inhabiting it will
become lethargic.

A2-031.name: Swinub
A2-031.text:
It rubs its snout on the ground to find and dig up
food. It sometimes discovers hot springs.

A2-032.name: Piloswine

ability.effect: This Pokémon takes −20 damage from attacks from or Pokémon.

A2-032.text:
If it charges at an enemy, the hairs on its back
stand up straight. It is very sensitive to sound.

A2-033.name: Mamoswine

ability.effect: This Pokémon takes −30 damage from attacks from or Pokémon.

A2-033.text:
This Pokémon can be spotted in wall paintings
from as far back as 10,000 years ago. For a
while, it was thought to have gone extinct.

A2-039.name: Floatzel

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 30 more damage.

A2-039.text:
With its flotation sac inflated, it can carry people
on its back. It deflates the sac before it dives.

A2-042.name: Finneon

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from—and effects of—attacks done to this Pokémon.

A2-042.text:
The line running down its side can store sunlight.
It shines vividly at night.

A2-043.name: Lumineon
A2-043.text:
With its shining light, it lures its prey close.
However, the light also happens to attract
ferocious fish Pokémon—its natural predators.

A2-044.name: Snover

attack.effect: If your opponent's Active Pokémon is a {F} Pokémon, this attack does 30 more damage.

A2-044.text:
During cold seasons, it migrates to the
mountain’s lower reaches. It returns to the
snow-covered summit in the spring.

A2-045.name: Abomasnow
A2-045.text:
It lives a quiet life on mountains that are
perpetually covered in snow. It hides itself
by whipping up blizzards.

A2-047.name: Wash Rotom
A2-047.text:
This Rotom has entered a washing machine.
It nods with satisfaction after it floods the
surrounding area.

A2-048.name: Frost Rotom

attack.effect: This attack also does 10 damage to each of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A2-048.text:
This Rotom has entered a refrigerator. It leaps
around gleefully after it uses cold air to freeze
the area around it.

A2-051.name: Magnemite
A2-051.text:
The electromagnetic waves emitted by the units
at the sides of its head expel antigravity, which
allows it to float.

A2-052.name: Magneton
A2-052.text:
Three Magnemite are linked by a strong magnetic
force. Earaches will occur if you get too close.

A2-053.name: Magnezone

attack.effect: Discard a {L} Energy from this Pokémon.

A2-053.text:
As it zooms through the sky, this Pokémon seems
to be receiving signals of unknown origin while
transmitting signals of unknown purpose.

A2-055.name: Electrode
A2-055.text:
The more energy it charges up, the faster
it gets. But this also makes it more likely
to explode.

A2-056.name: Electabuzz

attack.effect: Take a {L} Energy from your Energy Zone and attach it to this Pokémon.

A2-056.text:
Many power plants keep Ground-type Pokémon
around as a defense against Electabuzz that
come seeking electricity.

A2-057.name: Electivire

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has at least 2 extra {L} Energy attached, this attack does 80 more damage.

A2-057.text:
The amount of electrical energy this Pokémon
produces is proportional to the rate of its pulse.
The voltage jumps while Electivire is battling.

A2-058.name: Shinx

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from—and effects of—attacks done to this Pokémon.

A2-058.text:
The extension and contraction of its muscles
generates electricity. It glows when in trouble.

A2-059.name: Luxio
A2-059.text:
Strong electricity courses through the tips of
its sharp claws. A light scratch causes fainting
in foes.

A2-060.name: Luxray

attack.effect: Discard all {L} Energy from this Pokémon. This attack does 120 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon.

A2-060.text:
It can see clearly through walls to track down its
prey and seek its lost young.

A2-061.name: Pachirisu ex

attack.effect: If this Pokémon has a Pokémon Tool attached, this attack does 40 more damage.

A2-061.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A2-063.name: Togepi
A2-063.text:
The shell seems to be filled with joy. It is said
that it will share good luck when treated kindly.

A2-065.name: Togekiss

attack.effect: During your next turn, this Pokémon's Overdrive Smash attack does +60 damage.

A2-065.text:
These Pokémon are never seen anywhere near
conflict or turmoil. In recent times, they’ve hardly
been seen at all.

A2-068.name: Ralts

attack.effect: Switch this Pokémon with 1 of your Benched Pokémon.

A2-068.text:
The horns on its head provide a strong power
that enables it to sense people’s emotions.

A2-069.name: Kirlia
A2-069.text:
It has a psychic power that enables it to distort
the space around it and see into the future.

A2-070.name: Duskull
A2-070.text:
If it finds bad children who won’t listen to their
parents, it will spirit them away—or so it’s said.

A2-071.name: Dusclops
A2-071.text:
It seeks drifting will-o’-the-wisps and sucks them
into its empty body. What happens inside is
a mystery.

A2-072.name: Dusknoir

ability.effect: As often as you like during your turn, you may choose 1 of your Pokémon that has damage on it, and move all of its damage to this Pokémon.

A2-072.text:
At the bidding of transmissions from the spirit
world, it steals people and Pokémon away.
No one knows whether it has a will of its own.

A2-073.name: Drifloon

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes −20 damage from attacks.

A2-073.text:
It is whispered that any child who mistakes
Drifloon for a balloon and holds on to it could
wind up missing.

A2-074.name: Drifblim
A2-074.text:
Some say this Pokémon is a collection of souls
burdened with regrets, silently drifting through
the dusk.

A2-083.name: Gligar
A2-083.text:
It usually clings to cliffs. When it spots its prey,
it spreads its wings and glides down to attack.

A2-084.name: Gliscor

attack.effect: Flip 2 coins. This attack does 20 more damage for each heads.

A2-084.text:
It observes prey while hanging inverted from
branches. When the chance presents itself,
it swoops!

A2-085.name: Hitmontop
A2-085.text:
It launches kicks while spinning. If it spins at high
speed, it may bore its way into the ground.

A2-086.name: Nosepass
A2-086.text:
It moves less than an inch a year, but when
it’s in a jam, it will spin and drill down into the
ground in a split second.

A2-088.name: Cranidos
A2-088.text:
A primeval Pokémon, it possesses a hard and
sturdy skull, lacking any intelligence within.

A2-089.name: Rampardos

attack.effect: If your opponent's Pokémon is Knocked Out by damage from this attack, this Pokémon also does 50 damage to itself.

A2-089.text:
In ancient times, people would dig up fossils of
this Pokémon and use its skull, which is harder
than steel, to make helmets.

A2-090.name: Wormadam
A2-090.text:
Its appearance changes depending on where it
evolved. The materials on hand become a part of
its body.

A2-091.name: Riolu
A2-091.text:
They communicate with one another using their
auras. They are able to run all through the night.

A2-092.name: Lucario

ability.effect: Attacks used by your Pokémon do +20 damage to your opponent’s Active Pokémon.

A2-092.text:
It’s said that no foe can remain invisible to
Lucario, since it can detect auras—even those
of foes it could not otherwise see.

A2-095.name: Gallade ex

attack.effect: This attack does 20 more damage for each Energy attached to your opponent's Active Pokémon.

A2-095.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A2-096.name: Murkrow
A2-096.text:
Feared and loathed by many, it is believed to
bring misfortune to all those who see it at night.

A2-097.name: Honchkrow

attack.effect: This attack does 50 damage to 1 of your opponent's Pokémon.

A2-097.text:
It is merciless by nature. It is said that it never
forgives the mistakes of its Murkrow followers.

A2-101.name: Mightyena
A2-101.text:
It will always obey the commands of a skilled
Trainer. Its behavior arises from its living in packs
in ancient times.

A2-102.name: Stunky
A2-102.text:
It sprays a foul fluid from its rear. Its stench
spreads over a mile radius, driving Pokémon
away.

A2-103.name: Skuntank

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Poisoned.

A2-103.text:
It attacks by spraying a horribly smelly fluid from
the tip of its tail. Attacks from above confound it.

A2-105.name: Skorupi
A2-105.text:
After burrowing into the sand, it waits patiently
for prey to come near. This Pokémon and
Sizzlipede share common descent.

A2-107.name: Croagunk

attack.effect: Flip a coin for each Pokémon you have in play. This attack does 20 damage for each heads.

A2-107.text:
Inflating its poison sacs, it fills the area with an
odd sound and hits flinching opponents with a
poison jab.

A2-108.name: Toxicroak

attack.effect: Flip a coin for each Pokémon you have in play. This attack does 40 damage for each heads.

A2-108.text:
Swaying and dodging the attacks of its foes, it
weaves its flexible body in close, then lunges
out with its poisonous claws.

A2-109.name: Darkrai

attack.effect: Your opponent's Active Pokémon is now Asleep.

A2-109.text:
It chases people and Pokémon from its territory by
causing them to experience deep,
nightmarish slumbers.

A2-110.name: Darkrai ex

ability.effect: Whenever you attach a Energy from your Energy Zone to this Pokémon, do 20 damage to your opponent’s Active Pokémon.

A2-110.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A2-112.name: Registeel
A2-112.text:
Registeel’s body is made of a strange material
that is flexible enough to stretch and shrink but
also more durable than any metal.

A2-116.name: Bronzor
A2-116.text:
Ancient people believed that the pattern on
Bronzor’s back contained a mysterious power.

A2-117.name: Bronzong

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes −20 damage from attacks.

A2-117.text:
In ages past, this Pokémon was revered as a
bringer of rain. It was found buried in the ground.

A2-119.name: Dialga ex

attack.effect: Take 2 {M} Energy from your Energy Zone and attach it to 1 of your Benched Pokémon.

A2-119.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A2-120.name: Heatran

attack.effect: This Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

A2-120.text:
It dwells in volcanic caves. It digs in with its
cross-shaped feet to crawl on ceilings and walls.

A2-126.name: Eevee

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, this attack does 20 more damage.

A2-126.text:
Its ability to evolve into many forms allows it to
adapt smoothly and perfectly to any environment.

A2-130.name: Aipom
A2-130.text:
As it did more and more with its tail, its hands
became clumsy. It makes its nest high in
the treetops.

A2-135.name: Bidoof

attack.effect: Halve your opponent's Active Pokémon's remaining HP, rounded down.

A2-135.text:
With nerves of steel, nothing can perturb it. It is
more agile and active than it appears.

A2-136.name: Bibarel
A2-136.text:
It busily makes its nest with stacks of branches and
roots it has cut up with its sharp incisors.

A2-137.name: Buneary
A2-137.text:
If both of Buneary’s ears are rolled up, something
is wrong with its body or mind. It’s a sure sign the
Pokémon is in need of care.

A2-138.name: Lopunny

attack.effect: This attack also does 20 damage to 1 of your opponent's Benched Pokémon.

A2-138.text:
Lopunny is constantly monitoring its surroundings.
If danger approaches, this Pokémon responds
with superdestructive kicks.

A2-142.name: Fan Rotom

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, put your opponent's Active Pokémon into their hand.

A2-142.text:
This Rotom has entered an electric fan. It smirks
with satisfaction over a prank well pulled after it
blows away everything around it.

A2-144.name: Skull Fossil
A2-144.rule: You may play any number of Item cards during your turn.

A2-146.name: Pokémon Communication
A2-146.rule: You may play any number of Item cards during your turn.

A2-151.name: Team Galactic Grunt
A2-151.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A2-153.name: Volkner
A2-153.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A2-154.name: Dawn
A2-154.rule: You may play only 1 Supporter card during your turn.

A2-156.name: Tangrowth

attack.effect: Heal 30 damage from this Pokémon.

A2-156.text:
Tangrowth has two arms that it can extend as it
pleases. Recent research has shown that these
arms are, in fact, bundles of vines.

A2-157.name: Combee

attack.effect: Put 1 random Basic Pokémon from your deck onto your Bench.

A2-157.text:
At night, Combee sleep in a group of about a
hundred, packed closely together in a lump.

A2-159.name: Shaymin

ability.effect: Once during your turn, you may heal 10 damage from each of your Pokémon.

A2-159.text:
It can dissolve toxins in the air to instantly
transform ruined land into a lush field of flowers.

A2-160.name: Mamoswine

ability.effect: This Pokémon takes −30 damage from attacks from or Pokémon.

A2-160.text:
This Pokémon can be spotted in wall paintings
from as far back as 10,000 years ago. For a
while, it was thought to have gone extinct.

A2-163.name: Shinx

attack.effect: Flip a coin. If heads, during your opponent's next turn, prevent all damage from—and effects of—attacks done to this Pokémon.

A2-163.text:
The extension and contraction of its muscles
generates electricity. It glows when in trouble.

A2-165.name: Drifloon

attack.effect: During your opponent's next turn, this Pokémon takes −20 damage from attacks.

A2-165.text:
It is whispered that any child who mistakes
Drifloon for a balloon and holds on to it could
wind up missing.

A2-166.name: Mesprit

attack.effect: You can use this attack only if you have Uxie and Azelf on your Bench. Discard all Energy from this Pokémon.

A2-166.text:
Known as “The Being of Emotion.” It taught
humans the nobility of sorrow, pain, and joy.

A2-170.name: Lucario

ability.effect: Attacks used by your Pokémon do +20 damage to your opponent’s Active Pokémon.

A2-170.text:
It’s said that no foe can remain invisible to
Lucario, since it can detect auras—even those
of foes it could not otherwise see.

A2-173.name: Croagunk

attack.effect: Flip a coin for each Pokémon you have in play. This attack does 20 damage for each heads.

A2-173.text:
Inflating its poison sacs, it fills the area with an
odd sound and hits flinching opponents with a
poison jab.

A2-174.name: Heatran

attack.effect: This Pokémon also does 20 damage to itself.

A2-174.text:
It dwells in volcanic caves. It digs in with its
cross-shaped feet to crawl on ceilings and walls.

A2-177.name: Bidoof

attack.effect: Halve your opponent's Active Pokémon's remaining HP, rounded down.

A2-177.text:
With nerves of steel, nothing can perturb it. It is
more agile and active than it appears.

A2-179.name: Regigigas

attack.effect: This attack does more damage equal to the damage this Pokémon has on it.

A2-179.text:
It is said to have made Pokémon that look like
itself from a special ice mountain, rocks,
and magma.

A2-180.name: Yanmega ex

attack.effect: Discard a random Energy from this Pokémon.

A2-180.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.

A2-202.rule: When your Pokémon ex is Knocked Out, your opponent gets 2 points.
